e":"Finch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>finch</i>, <i>fink</i> ‘finch’ (Old English <i>finc</i>), for a small, lively, cheerful person.","Americanized form (translation into English) of German, Jewish (Ashkenazic), Czech, Slovenian, and Croatian   Fink   ‘finch’, or of some of the corresponding Slavic surnames, e.g. Czech (Moravian) <b>Pěnka</b> (see   Penka  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Fink","meanings":["German, Jewish (Ashkenazic), Danish, and English: nickname for a lively and cheerful person, or, in the case of the Jewish name, an artificial name, from Middle High German <i>vinke</i>, Middle English and Yiddish <i>fink</i> ‘finch’ (see   Finch   and   Vink  ). The surname of German origin is also found in some central European countries, for example in Czechia, Slovenia, and Croatia, often as a translation into German of corresponding Slavic nicknames or surnames. In part, this is a Gottscheerish (i.e. Gottschee German) surname, originating from the Kočevsko region in Lower Carniola, Slovenia (see   Kocevar  )."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":44,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":53,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Finch was born in 1505, in Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Nicholas Finch and Alice Lawney. She had at least 2 daughters with Thomas Carpenter. She died in 1564, in Hertfordshire, England, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1505–1564":"1505–1564","1500–1581":"1500–1581","1522–1615":"1522–1615","1542–1615":"1542–1615","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1558":"1558","1522":"1522","1500":"1500","1542":"1542","1564":"1564","1581":"1581","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","1615":"1615",", Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England"},"fi":{"1505–1564":"1505–1564","1500–1581":"1500–1581","1522–1615":"1522–1615","1542–1615":"1542–1615","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1558":"1558","1522":"1522","1500":"1500","1542":"1542","1564":"1564","1581":"1581","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","1615":"1615",", Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England"},"fr":{"1505–1564":"1505–1564","1500–1581":"1500–1581","1522–1615":"1522–1615","1542–1615":"1542–1615","–Male":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1558":"1558","1522":"1522","1500":"1500","1542":"1542","1564":"1564","1581":"1581","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","1615":"1615",", Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Margaret Finch est née en 1505, à Hertfordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fille de Nicholas Finch et Alice Law